  "texts": [
    "(A4)Analogously, we find for the kinetic energy:E c kin (t → ∞) = - 2t 2 0 J + 1 L t 2 0 J.",
    "(A5)In Fig. 15, we observe a gap between ground state and excited states, which is proportional to the exchange coupling [32].characterized by the coupling constant γ q, with q representing the wavevector of the emitted excitation in one dimension.",
    "In general, the tensor can be defined as:γ q = -iωf (ω q) ⟨e| ÔT LS |g⟩ • êq (B1)where ω is the energy difference between the excited and ground states, f (ω q) is the density of states at the energy of the emitted excitation, ÔT LS is the operator that couples the TLS to the bath, and êq is the polarization vector associated with the emitted excitation, orthogonal to q.",
    "To study the relaxation dynamics, we focus on the time evolution of the population inversion operatorσ e→g = (|g⟩ ⟨g| -|e⟩ ⟨e|) (B2)which tracks the transition probability between the two levels.",
    "A standard method to derive its dynamics is to use the Robertson projection operator technique [90,91], which projects the full density matrix evolution onto the relevant subspace spanned by σ e→g."
  ]
